description:
In lora_l2.c:87-93, hwinfo_get_device_id() returns ssize_t. The code checks if hwid_len <= 0, but does not check if hwid_len exceeds the buffer size (16 bytes). While hwinfo_get_device_id() SHOULD respect the sizeof(hwid) argument, defensive coding requires validating the return value does not exceed the buffer.

Location: firmware/bridge-zephyr/subsys/lichen/lora_l2.c:87-93

Code flow:
hwid_len = hwinfo_get_device_id(hwid, sizeof(hwid));  // hwid is 16 bytes
if (hwid_len <= 0) { ... }
// hwid_len cast to size_t on line 105
tc_sha256_update(&sha_state, hwid, (size_t)hwid_len);

If hwinfo_get_device_id() misbehaves and returns a value > 16 (due to driver bug), tc_sha256_update() would read past the hwid buffer, causing an out-of-bounds read.

Impact: Out-of-bounds read if Zephyr hwinfo driver misbehaves. Defense-in-depth issue. The attacker cannot control hwinfo_get_device_id() return value remotely.

Fix: Add check: if (hwid_len > sizeof(hwid)) { LOG_ERR(...); return -EINVAL; }
